Fail Successfully

{Rebundling of a presentation created and delivered by Mike Woodburne (mwoodburne@mawtechnology.com), Ron Clapman (ron.clapman@forgerock.com), and Robert Faller (robert.faller@forgerock.com)}

That sure is a dumb title ain't it? Who would ever do anything thinking they will fail?


Guess what - we all will. We will try to prevent the obvious but as they say "$4!+ happens!".

Even Amazon acknowledges this. From "AWS Well-Architected Framework" of November 2017 ( https://d0.awsstatic.com/whitepapers/architecture/AWS_Well-Architected_Framework.pdf ):

In any system of reasonable complexity it is expected that failures will occur, and it is generally of interest to know how to become aware of these failures, respond to them, and prevent them from happening again.

The "system of reasonable complexity" part cracks me up. Name one "system" that is not complex.  And then interconnect these "systems". Amazing anything works long enough to fail.

Failure is patient. It can be because it knows eventually the ideal moment will arrive. Failure is inevitable. While the goal is to prevent failure as much as possible we must be prepared when we can't.

At ForgeRock our goal is to help our customers be successful. This includes highlighting potential but preventable issues. This chart represents feedback from the ForgeRock Support team as to what types of preventable root causes they see most often. These data points are discussed further below.

What stands out is that close to half of the preventable fails are the basics - read the docs, training, and testing.

Since failure is inevitable (why we have personal insurance) it is best to deal with it directly. Here are the four topics to Fail Successfully, with Prevent being the highest priority (and what we will discuss the most) as well as what to do when "fail" overcomes "prevent":

  1. Prevent the failure in the first place

  2. Be Prepared

  3. Monitor everything; know "normal"

  4. Respond with a plan, not in panic

Flow of this Content

In the following we look at a few cases where failure was turned into success. We then look at some epic failures with a focus on ways they could have been prevented with relevance to today's production deployments. For completeness we suggest ways to prevent issues with the ForgeRock platform as well as ways to deal with unpreventable issues. While the content is organized to build upon itself please feel free to use these links if you prefer to jump around a bit:

Real Life - Examples of Successful Failures

Knowing failure can be around the next corner let's be realistic and be prepared the best we can to succeed. Successful failures will be ones we survive, learn the most from, and do not repeat. Here are three examples of failing successfully:

  1. Apollo 13 - "Houston we've had a problem" ( https://www.google.com/search?client=safari&rls=en&q=apollo+13&ie=UTF-8&oe=UTF-8 )
    https://www.forbes.com/sites/geoffloftus/2013/04/03/apollo-13-lessons-from-the-successful-failure/#615d2be15d0b
    https://www.scribd.com/document/9612390/APOLLO-13-Problem-Solution-Management

  2. US Airways Flight 1549 - "Miracle on the Hudson" ( https://www.google.com/search?client=safari&rls=en&q=flight+1549&ie=UTF-8&oe=UTF-8 )

  3. First Responders ( https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Certified_first_responder )

Let's quickly explore these three examples.

Apollo 13

Three well trained folks headed to the moon when at about 205,000 miles from the nearest service station (as well as air to breathe) an oxygen tank fails.

Not good. 

In the process of failing the oxygen tank takes out a couple of fuel cells.

Really not good.

But there is no need to retell a well known story. 

What is important is that even with a major system failure and extremely limited means to succeed the highly trained and highly motivated folks aboard Apollo 13 made it back to earth successfully. They did not achieve their mission to land on the moon but under the circumstances "success" was quickly redefined and priorities changed.


US Airways Flight 1549

The "Miracle on the Hudson" is a lesson on turning chopped geese and ice water into something palatable.

Goose #1 into engine 1 of 2 = bad.

Goose #2 into engine 2 of 2 = very bad.

Distance to nearest runway > loss of altitude of a plane with two destroyed, non-operating engines = very, very, bad.

Quiet, calm stretch of water + experienced flight crew = let's land this thing on the Hudson River.

This failure, a crippled aircraft full of passengers over a major metropolitan area, had disaster written all over it. Again there is no reason to retell a well documented story. But there are points worth noting:

  • Handling the unexpected is as important as preparing for it. Prior to this incident this type of event - two destroyed engines during takeoff - was not part of any training procedures. In fact when attempting to recreate the event in flight simulators it took one crew many times before they were actually successful.

  • Failing successfully is a team effort. Captain Sullenberger credits the crew and passengers with helping him create a situation where everyone survived.

  • Forensics is very important. Not only to help understand and prepare accordingly for the next possible failure but to also point out that everyone involved did the best that they could under the circumstances.

Flight 1549 did not obtain the original objective of landing in Charlotte, North Carolina but this is definitely an example of a successful failure.


First Responders

First Responders are highly trained, highly skilled, experienced individuals who are part of a focused and motivated team with open communications making quick decisions and executing on those decisions.

While every event First Responders are engaged in is different there is a developed process of dealing with these events. There are common ways to deal with injuries and trauma during these events.

Training and process may not align perfectly with each event but the skill set and experience enables the First Responders to optimize the chance of success no matter what failure they have been called to address.


During a Fail - Conflicts of Interest

Mentioning First Responders brings up another topic that needs to be addressed and is often witnessed when a failure occurs in a production environment - conflicts of interest.

During a major fail - as when a train derailed in Washington state recently - there is a set of priorities:

  1. Save people - First Responders

  2. Figure out what happened - Forensics

  3. Get traffic moving again - Service delivery such as the highway department

As can be imagined the process of saving people will probably have an adverse effect on evidence collection that could be used to understand what happened. Saving people will also have a priority over getting traffic moving again.

While the priorities are obvious where human life is involved, not so when a production system fails. All too often the process of recovering the system means any forensic data (log files, memory dumps, system stats, etc) is lost. With little forensic data and people in panic mode, changes are made to the system without an understanding as to what exactly the changes are being made for. A "Whatever it takes to get traffic moving again!" attitude can prevail.

It is a bit like pushing the train back on the tracks, throwing the injured humans on-board, and then traveling at even a higher rate of speed so the arrival at the next stop will be on time and all the injured passengers will be miraculously healed. Ain't gonna happen. But at least the vehicular traffic on the highway is moving along nicely, right?

For a production system to fail successfully the team must be prepared to take the proper steps, in the proper order, to successfully get the systems back running BUT at the same time ensuring that all the predefined forensic data is collected and minimizing the impact on the existing systems. Not an easy task but practically impossible if the proper training and process is not in place BEFORE the unexpected but expected failure occurs.


Real Life - Examples of Epic Failures

Unfortunately many epic failures do not have a successful side. Let's take a stroll through history and discuss some epic fails. Why revisit the past? Have you seen this quote?

“Those who cannot remember the past are condemned to repeat it." (George Santayana)

Each one of the following examples has good amount of content available on the web so we will dispense with the details but instead point out the mistakes and what may have prevented the fail. The epic fails are:

  1. Fidenae Amphitheater Collapse of 27AD with 20,000 human fatalities
    https://www.google.com/search?q=fidenae+stadium+disaster&oq=fidenae+stadium+disaster

  2. Halifax Explosion of 1917 with 1,950 human fatalities
    https://www.google.com/search?q=halifax+explosion&oq=halifax+exp
    http://newsinteractives.cbc.ca/halifaxexplosion/

  3. Banqiao Dam Collapse of 1975 with 25,000 to 230,000 human fatalities
    https://www.google.com/search?q=banqiao+dam+disaster&oq=banqi  

  4. Tenerife Airport Disaster of 1977 with 583 human fatalities
    https://www.google.com/search?q=tenerife+airport+disaster&oq=tener+disaster  

  5. Bradford City Stadium Fire of 1985 with 56 human fatalities
    https://www.google.com/search?q=bradford+city+stadium+fire&oq=bradford+city+stadium+

Four of the five fails were caused directly by humans. In the case of #3 the Banqiao Dam Collapse certainly was exacerbated by humans. Unfortunately all of these fails have similar characteristics to many of the failures we see everyday in today's production environments.


Fidenae Amphitheater Collapse - Physics do matter

In 27AD the ban on Gladiator events was going to be lifted. An "entrepreneur" of the time, anticipating the pent up demand for audiences wanting to enjoy a good time watching other people attempting to kill each other, hurriedly funded the building of a 50,000 seat amphitheater. The entrepreneur did not worry about things like physics or the proper construction of such a venue. Nope. The two things that were top of mind was the budget and timeline. Needed to have the amphitheater built and ready to go when the Gladiator ban was lifted.

What happened? First gladiator event drew a full house and the amphitheater collapsed killing 20,000 potential spectators. Not the best way to attract future season ticket holders.

Ways to PREVENT this type of fail:

  1. Call out risks early and often. Do this in archived emails. Make sure the warnings are reaching the stakeholders. It is better to have been annoyingly persistent before a fail than one of those "I knew this would happen" whiners after.

  2. Pick two, not three, ONLY two (we hope c is included in your choice):

    1. Cheap

    2. Quick

    3. Reliable

  3. Insane deadlines = bad behavior. The deadlines may seem possible when things started up, tough but possible. And you are the type that likes a challenge. Make it too easy, too obtainable, and the challenge is just not there. Get real. Running a production environment is not a competition. If the deadlines are insane or have the potential of being insane if just one item misses a target date then say so (and email and document).

  4. Certain deployment methods are not meant for all deployments. Sprint | Agile methodologies may be wonderful for some projects but are not always best for infrastructure.

  5. Budget - time and money - properly. If the project was not budgeted for properly that is an issue unto itself, but if you concede to using a cheaper solution (e.g. fewer servers, less time spent on performance testing, etc) you can guarantee that you are going to have issues associated with it that will ultimately require remediation. That remediation won’t be free and will likely cost more in the long run (think $ impact on customer satisfaction or employee productivity).

Next time you head off to your local, brand-new venue to watch the event of your choosing hope that the contractor's top criteria was "reliable".

https://www.google.com/search?q=fidenae+stadium+disaster&oq=fidenae+stadium+disaster


Halifax Explosion - Small deviations leads to big fail

Halifax, Nova Scotia, Canada experienced an explosion equivalent to 3,000 tons of TNT when a cargo ship carrying munitions for World War I blew up. The resulting explosion exceeded 9,000 degrees Fahrenheit and created a 50 foot tall tidal wave.

What caused such a major fail?

Unlike the Fidenae Amphitheater which was easily traceable to an individual's demands and disregard the Halifax event was much like things we see today in production deployment fails. It is death by a thousand cuts with the responsible parties unknowingly making small contributions to the large epic fail. Had anyone of those involved done one small thing differently, had the timing been changed by a mere minute or two, or were it not for the context of the period (during a major world war) this fail would not have happened.

Ways to PREVENT this type of fail:

  1. Small errors can lead to a very large fail. We have all been there and heard the little voice telling us that something is not quite right. And generally we ignore it, pushing forward towards the goal. But you are here reading this and discovering the little voice has many friends. The next time you hear the little voice recall the Halifax Explosion. How close is a small error to a major fail?

  2. Do not be afraid to stop. It’s okay to realize that there are shortcomings and flaws in how things were designed/executed on, but you need to know when to stop before things are beyond your control. When an issue arises, assess what subsequent action(s) could exacerbate the situation, estimate the likelihood and the impact of the occurrence, and then make an informed decision on risk. When calculating that risk, always factor in the unexpected.

  3. Understand the potential and scope of failure. It is good to build appropriate error handling in to your processes during design and execution. It is bad to assume that those handled errors represent all that could go wrong. Maintain historical knowledge on how the environment operates normally. Know when something new or different enters the landscape. Deviations from normal operation should receive heightened focus as the opportunity for failure increases.

  4. Over communicate. Architects and project managers need to be made aware of the issues and shortcomings experienced in the project in order to ensure that they are able to mitigate the risks associated with those issues. Knowledge of failures that have been experienced by other teams on the project can help reduce the likelihood that their failures greatly impact their peers.

  5. Assure ownership and leadership. One of the heroes of the Halifax Explosion was Vincent Coleman a railway dispatcher whose office was located very near the spot where the burning ship grounded. Vincent Coleman stayed his post, telegraphing the incoming train loaded with 300 passengers to halt before entering Halifax. Vincent Coleman's Morse code message to the train was:

    "Hold up the train. Ammunition ship afire in harbour making for Pier 6 and will explode. Guess this will be my last message. Good-bye boys."

    Unfortunately Vincent Coleman was correct on both accounts - the ship exploded and that was his last message.

The Halifax Explosion exemplifies many of the fails we see in production environments. Small, what seem like disconnected issues, start affecting each other. A system that runs out of disk space or a network connection that is intermittently interrupted start to cause other components to operate outside of the norm. Production environments are like busy harbors or airports - as long as everything goes as planned all is good. Deviations from said plan, no matter how small or seemingly insignificant are cause for concern.

https://www.google.com/search?q=halifax+explosion&oq=halifax+exp
http://newsinteractives.cbc.ca/halifaxexplosion/





















Banqiao Dam Collapse - Domino-effect

The unbreakable dam did. With good reason. The dam was scoped to handle 300mm of rain per day. A heavy storm that was passing through the area was stalled due to a weather front to the north. This storm dropped 1,060mm of rain per day - 3x to 4x the amount of rainfall expected. The Banqiao Dam was not alone on this drainage system; there were a number of smaller dams upstream. As the rain fell the upstream dams started to fail. These failures lead to even heavier flow to those dams further downstream. The domino effect was in full swing and accelerating. It was time to broadcast an evacuation order to all residents living below the Banqiao Dam. One problem - the heavy storm had also taken down the communication lines. A complete failure and no way to warn anyone; a high casualty rate was guaranteed.

Ways to PREVENT this type of fail:

  1. Assume peak load at worst possible time. Don’t build with the mindset that having just enough servers to handle an increased load is appropriate. Ask yourself what will happen if that increased load comes at a time when one or more servers are experiencing issues. Work with stakeholders to understand the impact if the system fails.

  2. Understand effect of component failure. Have an operations team that is comfortable with what failures look like. Know that if people are reporting symptom X on system Y, it may actually be due to an issue with system Z. Your system may be on the brink of failure due to another system. We have seen the failure of monitoring systems actually cause a failure on core production systems. Follow failures "upstream".

  3. Environment can handle unexpected load. Success is wonderful. Your new service was released and customers are pouring in. Maybe pouring in a bit more than expected. Maybe a lot more than expected. And then someone releases bots against your site. Meanwhile your cloud provider decides a few of your instances do not appear healthy so they take them offline. Sound crazy? Not hardly. Been there, done that. When this happens to your environment how will it handle it? Unexpected load is tough – servers cost money, but not every project has the means to add systems on demand. Look at a cost benefit analysis to determine where (if at all) to invest the time and resources.

  4. Well known alternative lines of communication and processes. You don’t want to be provisioning contractors access to communication systems while an issue is occuring. Same thing applies to system access – have a contingency plan in place (like a PAM system) in the event that your operations team is impacted and someone else needs elevated access to a system

As stated earlier this particular fail was not directly caused by humans but the casualty toll was most certainly exacerbated by human error. Those closest to the problem were not allowed to issue an evacuation order in a timely fashion. Permission to issue a warning was controlled by those concerned with more than just the humans below the dam. When permission was finally granted it was too late - the communication lines were already down. Sometimes those closest to the problem need the authority to act.

https://www.google.com/search?q=banqiao+dam+disaster&oq=banqi  


Tenerife Airport Disaster - Pausing is more than just ok

If the Halifax Explosion was death by a thousand cuts the Tenerife Airport Disaster was death by a thousand self-inflicted cuts. Little voices were screaming in unison - "ALL HELL IS ABOUT TO BREAK LOOSE!" but everyone was so busy dealing with a present situation they were deaf as well as blind and mute. This is a disaster that should have never happened.

But it did.

Tenerife (previously known as the Los Rodeos Airport) is not the primary airport on the Canary Islands. Gran Canaria Airport, on a neighboring island is. The Gran Canaria Airport is also frequented by Boeing 747s. Tenerife is not, and in fact it was not really equipped to handle 747s.

What started this tragedy was an unrelated terrorist bomb explosion at the Gran Canaria Airport which forced air traffic diversion to Tenerife. This diversion meant a significant increase of aircraft, many larger than the airport is meant to handle, descending on Tenerife.

Once at Tenerife let's refuel the aircraft.

Let's add fog to the overly congested Tenerife airport. Not just some wisps of fog but serious fog that brings visibility down to 100m/300ft for pilots who are not familiar with the airport.

You can see where this is going. And it keeps going with pilot to tower miscommunications and aircraft being "parked" in the active runway.

Why someone did not stand up and yell "Hold Everything!" is unclear.

Ways to PREVENT this type of fail:

  1. Arrogance is deadly. There were numerous times when this cascade of errors could have been stopped. Those involved were overly confident of their abilities and assumptions. Know your limitations.

  2. Identify the unseen. What you don't know or can't see can definitely hurt you. Acknowledge that uncharted territory is being entered and adjustments to plans and timeline may be needed. When reviewing logs, be able to identify true failures. It’s not uncommon to have behavior in an environment that results in false failures, so be sure to call that activity out when relying on others to help.

  3. Ask questions. Start by asking the obvious "dumb" questions. Don't be satisfied by "we have it covered" push offs. Question asking is bi-directional. Document questions and responses.

  4. Over communicate and assure message is heard and understood. Also bi-directional and documented. Assume that your message got lost over the wire unless you get a response back (SYN/SYN-ACK/ACK).

Unlike the Halifax Explosion where weather did not enter the equation, the fog did have a hand in the Tenerife Airport Disaster. Problem was that the fog issue was so obvious. Fog piled on top of all the other unusual circumstances should have mandated a complete pause of operations until the fog cleared. There is a place for bravado and the Tenerife Airport was not that place in 1977.

https://www.google.com/search?q=tenerife+airport+disaster&oq=tener+disaster


Bradford City Stadium Fire - Ignore it and it does not go away

"Oh, we'll get to that later" - until it comes and gets you sooner. The last major work done on the Bradford City Stadium was in 1908. The old wooden bleachers did not have risers allowing for an accumulation of rubbish including a lot of combustible trash. Modern fire suppression equipment was non-existent. The roof was covered with layers of highly-flammable material. And smoking was permitted.

Wonder what could possibly go wrong?

Not much until a spectator dropped a lit cigarette (by accident) onto the bleacher where the cigarette proceed to roll off the bleacher and into the trash just below. What was starting out as a boring game quickly, very quickly, became a fight for life.

Ways to PREVENT this type of fail:

  1. Upgrade often. Understand the product release cycle and the support period for the version you are on. Work upgrades in to the program roadmap. Know your environment and work to understand the level of effort associated with performing an upgrade so that you are prepared. Remember – as products evolve and introduce new functionality it complicates the upgrade path.

  2. Maintain the environment. Few people have a spotless house. It always helps to know what needs to be cleaned up and have a plan on how/when to do so. What may seem like a harmless network issue that causes minor, occasional, inconveniences may grow to a much larger issue as other variables change.

  3. Stop unsafe behavior or practices. Configuration changes need to be tracked as tightly as code changes (assuming code changes are being well tracked). Limited and audited administration accounts (not everyone should have the "root/superuser" password). Production and staging should be mirrors. Too often tickets are opened where something works as expected in one environment but not in the other.

  4. Temporary workarounds should only be temporary. It’s not uncommon to do things that don’t align with best practices as a temporary stop gap. Plans need to be in place to address those things. The longer they persist the more accepted they become.

The Bradford City Stadium fail points to a familiar issue - getting comfortable with the state of an environment; if it ain't broke don't fix it. Unfortunately becoming too comfortable can lead to an event that will force unscheduled, costly change.  

https://www.google.com/search?q=bradford+city+stadium+fire&oq=bradford+city+stadium+

Quote: It may be wise to brief Sponsors about the maintenance costs, ongoing operation and security maintenance, then periodic upgrades which require involvement from development teams and business testers. Without this ongoing investment there is a risk that the solution falls into disrepair, and availability degrades. - SE


There you have it. Five epic fails with at least four (80%) that were very much preventable. While preventable fails may vary for production deployments it is still a high percentage. Too high.

The following is an example of fail a ForgeRock customer experienced. It combines elements of Halifax and Tenerife (death by a thousand cuts), Banqiao (domino-effect), and Bradford (not fixing something in a timely fashion).

Real-life Incident report:

Organization-Z's environment was experiencing outages. We started with the OpenAM environment to uncover why they were having performance/reliability issues. Just a quick check to see if there might be something slightly awry. It was.

Settings in OpenAM told us that the next stop was the OpenDJ servers. Seemed that OpenAM had been configured to use an external CTS as well as an external configure store. Both of which were being hosted by the same OpenDJ instances. Of the three instances that were supposed to be in the replication topology (there was another OpenDJ instance in the replication agreement but it was not supposed to be there) one of the 4-core OpenDJ instances was 25% busy. The other two? One was 50% busy but its friend was 100% busy. The systems should in fact have been running at less than 10% busy based on the present user load. Seemed replication was having some issues. Not good. But why?

Checked the change logs and the replication status. One of the change logs was 82GB (that's GB as in giga) which would be understandable if we were managing the population of China. We weren't. This was for internal identities. And dsreplication was indicating that something was amiss. What was causing these huge replication loads? We know CTS can be a heavy load but not this heavy based on the usage profile.

Seems Organization-Z had used some non-production, "please-only-use-this-for-PoC-purposes" code as the basis for their code. The plugin let certain user groups know when their Active Directory password was going to expire and was extremely inefficient for production use. The code retrieves all the values for a user from the AD tree and therefore causes a token to be updated in OpenDJ for each value retrieved. The OpenAM session token became overly bloated, being updated often, and, because of the configuration, was being replicated across all OpenDJ nodes including the disaster recovery site which was offline occasionally.

Issues that helped enable this fail:

  • Organization-Z has significant environmental issues.

  • Product issues were impossible to discover and debug due to the interference of the environment and the difficulty to isolate.

  • There is only production; no dev or test or staging environments.

  • It can take six weeks to spin up a new virtual machine that will be “good network citizen” and recognized by the infrastructure (i.e. load balancers).

  • The people responsible for maintaining the service were not well equipped to adequately perform their duties:

    • Over-loaded with other tasks.

    • No environments or allocated time to learn products and points of integration.

    • Little to no documentation on how things are constructed.

    • A lot of responsibility but little authority (i.e. enforce best programming practices).

  • No load or functional testing.

  • No version controls.

  • Little or no certificate management. Certificates, while powerful and important to security, can easily take down an entire environment.

  • Too little involvement of Professional Services prior to issues.

  • Backups/image freezing were NOT implemented due to time constraints and more pressing issues.

  • Anything that should have only taken minutes took a few hours.

  • Time expectations are not aligned with reality.

Four Steps to Fail Successfully - Technical details

Back to the four topics to Fail Successfully:

  1. Prevent the failure in the first place

  2. Prepare for the unexpected

  3. Monitor everything and understand what "normal" looks like

  4. Respond with a plan, not in panic

Prevent

While the image of Smokey the Bear seems a bit out of place (compared to the previously mentioned fails) it captures critical aspects of prevention not mentioned when we examined the epic fails above. The image here is simple but then some of the basic ways to prevent failure are also simple.

First the forest is devastated but even as the "team" evaluates the root cause a new forest is already in place. Smokey and friends had a backup plan which was implemented as soon as possible. Probably some automated buildout scripts hosted in some versioning system.

The root cause of this event was an human being careless with a match thereby leading to a forest fire.

The fire was bad.

Maybe the Squirrel should have be more diligent watching for intruders. Perhaps the birds could have observed the smoke sooner. Too late for the blame game. Plus the fear of failure is very non-productive. Time for teamwork.

Root cause information is shared with the entire team with the hopes that if any of the team members observe the presence of another human with matches the potential failure can be halted immediately BEFORE fire erupts.

Finally note that one of the team members has already been trained on shovel usage. Not "if" but "when" a forest fire happens again they have a way to address the situation. This is important. Even if no more humans appear in the forest the training will still be needed; lightning strikes are a constant threat. While lightening is a different root cause of the forest fire but the actions to deal with the fire are the same.

The old saying still holds true:

"An ounce of prevention is worth a pound of cure."


In the examination of epic failures above we focused on ways to prevent the failure. These were not ForgeRock platform specific. To better understand what are the most preventable failures with regards to the ForgeRock platform we surveyed our own people. The ForgeRock Customer Success teams include Support Engineers and Customer Success Managers. These are the folks that are responsible for tickets opened by Partners and Customers with a support subscription. Over 60 people responded to the survey and provided many of the quotes. While the actual names of organizations and individuals were removed the comments/quotes are pretty much unfiltered. On to the survey responses.

Preventable issues

What are the most common preventable issues around the ForgeRock platform? The following list was presented to the ForgeRock Customer Success team:

  • Not reading the documentation

  • Lack of realistic testing

  • Lack of training on present version

  • Not monitoring logs

  • Improper tuning (i.e. JVM)

  • Production != staging

  • Unreasonable timelines

  • Network | Load Balancer issues

  • Replication mismanagement

  • Running out of disk space

  • Lack of version control

  • Certificate expiration

  • Abuse of "superuser" account

  • "Hidden" threshold enforcement (aka throttling)

  • Noisy neighbor

Those responding could rate the preventable issues, in their opinion, three ways:

  • Often

  • Sometimes

  • Seldom

For example those responding could rate "Not reading the documentation" as an issue that "Often", "Sometimes", or "Seldom" was attributed (root cause) of a preventable failure.

Two charts were generated from the responses. The pie chart (same as the one shown in the beginning) represents is a summation of the responses with Often = 2, Sometimes = 1, and Seldom = 0. Using this scoring "Lack of realistic testing" had a total score of 108 (9.6%). The bar chart provides a slightly different view of the same data. In this chart "Not reading the documentation" and "Lack of realistic testing" are the top "Often" culprits with "Running out of disk space" a "Sometimes" leader.

Let's touch on each issue in the order of how they were rated (per pie chart) and suggest the best way to prevent it from causing a failure in your environment.

Not reading ForgeRock documentation (10.3%)

We have all done it. Wait until the last minute when our back is up against the wall to find the operations manual. It is fine when we are talking about the TV remote right before the show you have been waiting for all week. It is a much different story when that unexpected storm takes out the power during the night and you need to get your brand new generator running.

And this is at the personal level…

When your 10 million customers are getting 404s and the executives are getting calls from the national news it is not time to search for "ForgeRock documentation".

Quotes:

Tricky to address via documentation when people don't read it (at least not until after the event, e.g. certificate expiry). - CSM

Many product questions are "How-To" and are solved with a link to a ForgeRock KB article. - SE

What ForgeRock can do:

Capture as much "tribal wisdom" as possible and make it available. This is what the Knowledge base is all about: https://backstage.forgerock.com/knowledge/kb/home

What can you do:

Take the time to review the product documentation as well as the Knowledge Base material. Don't need to read (at least not all of it) but at least know the location. Perhaps a bookmark or two. We do have tickets where the ForgeRock response is a link to a section in the documentation. Next entry in the ticket log is the customer asking that the ticket be closed as "solved".

We do know that the way information is presented and consumed is constantly evolving. Cave art has probably seen its peak. Help us provide material in the most consumable way. If you come across another vendor's way of transferring information that is better please let us know - docs@forgerock.com or open a ticket using your ForgeRock subscription.


Lack of realistic testing (9.6%)

You are about to embark on a road trip with your extended family. Lucky you. Yet you would never pack your sub-compact vehicle with the expected passenger load to determine if the van you will be actually using has the needed seating. Nope. Probably use the van to determine the capacity of said van.

Then why would the capacity of a production environment be determined by running things on someone's laptop?

Quotes:

A number of issues came about after the service had been running for a period of time, usually some type of resource leak; sessions, heap or file descriptors. These type of problems can be flushed out via ‘soak tests’ and also performing root cause analysis (RCA) for pre-prod failures as opposed to the common intervention to ‘bounce it.’ - SE

Invest in testing up-front and taking the approach to troubleshoot it when it breaks. - SM

There can be gaps in automated scripting/monitors to catch the 'easy' issues, out of disk space, detection of high resource usage, notification on expiration of key certs/licensing etc., notification of upcoming EOSL of products etc. - SM

Need to understand the ebbs and flows of “normal” usage to be alerted to anomalies which may point to nefarious activity. - TA

What ForgeRock can do:

We can do a better job of sharing best practices around load testing. This would include providing details in understanding how to determine when a component and the platform are under stress.

What can you do: Scheduling adequate time and resources for realistic testing based on well defined SLAs | SLOs. Easy to write, difficult to implement but well worth the time and effort.

https://techbeacon.com/5-best-practices-realistic-performance-testing


Lack of Training on present version (8.7%)

The feedback from the ForgeRock team was quite consistent and blunt - Get trained. Get trained on the version of the product you are deploying. Training MUST be factored into the schedule BEFORE production release. Even if a Partner is engaged for the deployment of the platform the people who will be operating the environment need adequate time to get training and to use that training to understand and "own" your deployment.

Quotes:

The lack of training definitely hurts but so does the lack of continuous training! A customer trained on AM 11 is going to fail with AM 13. Perhaps not in the same fashion as the customer who hasn't taken any training at all because they'll have some background and a foundation of knowledge yet they can fail just as well. Also, there's turnover within the customer so this is more of a constant discussion point so they are skilled enough to at least work with support. - CSM

Don't try to make the ForgeRock platform operate like a previous product. A "simple replacement" of a previous product can end up with forcing a new round peg into an old square hole. - CSM

Our main problem is with people configuring the environment in "unconventional" manners. "Bending" the product if you will or using specific versions of the software to meet their demands when they could be solved by upgrading / patching etc (but often reluctant based on release schedules). This is often due to lack of training or idea behind the authentication concepts. Although we cannot expect perfect environments, customers do sometimes end up building glass cannons that routinely need to be bandaged. - SE

A lack of training can lead to unrealistic expectations of what support will offer. Invest in getting up to speed on how to design and configure the product. - SM

A short course for new customer product admins of ForgeRock software, i.e. how to use BackStage to its fullest advantage. Most OpenIDM/IDM questions are "How-To" and are solved with a link to a ForgeRock KB article. - SE

Making sure all customer product admins take the instructor led ForgeRock classes in regards to the product(s) they will be interacting with and If that admin employee leaves that position (or company) and a new admin(s) replaces them; the new admin(s) need to receive the same training in a timely manner. - SE

What ForgeRock can do:

On multi-year deals, we should include annual training credits (and PS Packages for that matter). For now, customers can purchase additional training credits on successive years in a multi-year deal.

In addition, we will work to ensure that our training courses are kept up to date with content that is aligned with recently released versions of the software.

What can you do:

Simple - get trained. OJT (On the Job Training) as in when the alarms are going off and people are running around screaming may not be the best time to learn the product.

Not Monitoring Logs (8.5%)


Good news - ForgeRock products log everything!

Bad news - ForgeRock products log everything.

While most organizations do a good job of monitoring their environment using various mechanisms such as Splunk, ELK, Data Dog, and numerous other offerings, the challenge is leaving the graphs and driving headlong into the textual logs. 

Why is this important? The graph here is simulated data but represents some real life fails. The graph shows that the primary systems are definitely busy. As expected DR- C and DR-D (DR = disaster recovery) are not busy. BUT….

The graph does not easily show that DR-D is at 1% busy. The operating system of DR-D may be running and hence providing data back to the monitoring system but the services, for example directory services (DS), could be off. Which may not be a problem but DR-D is part of the DS replication topology for all four instances. While DS is off on DR-D the other systems, mostly the two active instances Primary-A and Primary-B, are holding changes waiting for DR-D to rejoin the world. This equates to added load and disk space consumption on the two primary systems.

It is the DS textual logs on DR-D that will help in discovering root cause as to why the DS service is off. It is command line tools such as dsreplication status that will highlight if there are replication issues.


Quotes:

Even worse than NOT monitoring logs is monitoring logs improperly! Customers don't understand the gravity of error conditions such as:

  • Is this error transient?

  • Should I be looking for a single instance of the error or a trend? - CSM

More around How to properly understand the logs and issues in them. - CSM

I think this is important. Many DS tickets can be resolved by looking at the logs. However even if the folks architecting the customer system understood LDAP fully (and that's a stretch) likely the ops team holding things together really have no idea and cannot interpret logs. - SE

We were quite thorough in the SDLC processes and fared well against the top preventable issues listed, but one issue turned up repeatedly. Often enough that I gave it a name; ‘Component monitoring.’ Enterprise monitoring  ran simulated user sessions which would alert when an applications failed. This would lead to a call out and when groups of AM integrated applications failed troubleshooting turned to AM. In the root cause analysis we saw many situations where there were indicators that AM was failing before the Enterprise Monitoring alerted. For example in the No-Single-Point of failure solution, one of a resilient pair of components could fail but there would be no alert (until the other failed). Service impact could have been avoided if ‘component level monitoring’ had been in place. Not just AM service monitoring (via LB) but functional checks on each of the constituent services; RP’s, AM, AM Agents, and DS. - SE

I am not sure it is monitoring of the logs as more of a "I don't know what I am supposed to be looking for". - CSM

What ForgeRock can do:

We could better documenting and/or providing KB articles on log topics. Some basic "how to read 'em" would be helpful.

What can you do:

Know what a "normal" usage pattern is for your environment. Do not rely solely on graphs for problem notification/discovery. Most definitely know where the logs are located and how to understand the information they contain. ForgeRock logs contain a wealth of information; mining that wealth takes some effort.

Production != staging (or testing) (8.1%)

"Our staging environment is a mirror of production." Heard this one many times. Knowing the difficulty in actually achieving this means we do not always take the statement as pure fact. There is always differences. They may be subtle but there are differences. Better to attempt to make them as close as possible and note the differences.

Quotes:

ForgeRock provided a customer with a script to run against an LDIF export to determine the difference between datasets on different DJ servers. Their engineer ran the script on a production server and crashed it. - CSM

Customer's "perf" environment where they run performance tests is their QA environment with 100s of developers and dozens of app teams working everyday. We clearly need to define these basic environments as a plank on the platform of success: DEV, QA, UAT, PERF, PROD. - CSM

While applications drive the business, controls to identity data MUST be adhered to - management of IAM systems should NOT be compromised to make development easier. Access control of REST/resource endpoints MUST:

  • be enforced

  • follow strict policies

  • accessed using identifiable credentials

  • institute the use of versioning

Developers MUST adhere to restrictions and controls mandated at a organizational level. - TA

Unreasonable timelines (7.8%)

Not sure what to say here. Sometimes more money, more people, more resources do not add up to shrinking time. Experience would say that sometimes the opposite effect happens. A large scale strategy is important but a defined set of quick wins can be as, if not more, important.

Technology can be complex and requires that the correct amount of time and resources are applied. But humans and legacy systems can have an unexpectedly high impact on timelines. Data cleansing and integration can also present significant speed bumps along the road to deployment. Mantra of the seasoned Program/Project Manager: Under commit and over deliver.

Quotes:

This needs to start in the beginning of the project | product acquisition phase for it to be effective. "You can do this in 3 months" should always have the disclaimer of "if you use an accredited partner and train your teams". - CSM

Following the initial implementation, there were a good many ‘bedding in issues’ so an idea was put forward to address those in a systematic way calling it a ‘stabilisation project.’ This amounted to collating all the support/development issues, prioritising against impact, than chasing down root cause for each one. When the list was short enough we closed the project. With hindsight, the formality of structuring and tracking the work with Operations Management sponsorship, was of significant value, turning the usual gripes about new systems into credibility for the project team for their rigour post implementation and positive talk about the new Access Management solution and Forgerock. As well as I know it is not typical to have such a stage in a project plan, but were I the technical lead again, I would advise that. - SE

Take time to eliminate:

  • Moving targets where the customer or other 3rd party integrations can't agree on design and constantly change the requirements

  • Requirements not properly documented and as such 'Requirement vs Deliverable' not aligned - CSM

What ForgeRock can do:

Push back. Sounds harsh but if success is the goal sometimes it is ok to pause and reset. Had the pilots and ground control done so at Tenerife it would have been just another delayed flight.

What can you do:

Listen. ForgeRock is not goaled on you meeting your timelines. We are a bit over the top on customer success and that is the basis of our feedback.


Network | Load Balancer issues (7.5%)

The ForgeRock platform is sensitive to the network configuration and operation. Load balancers, sticky sessions, etc all have a significant but hard-to-find hand in causing issues. As more environments are hosted in the cloud we are seeing a jump in network and load balancer related issues. Do not assume parity in capabilities between private environments and cloud-based (*aaS) services. Extreme testing is HIGHLY recommended. In some cases cloud-based services have warm-up periods as well as threshold limits | throttling that can have a big impact on performance.

Some of the most time consuming and frustrating tickets are those whose root cause is the network and/or load balancer.

Quotes:

This one drives us all nuts from the clear "can't be the network" to non-cooperation between groups within the customer. - CSM

Customers not really understanding Stateful session vs Stateless session needs and issues. - CSM

If there is something wrong with the network identity management software will find it. - TA

What ForgeRock can do:

Not much ForgeRock can do here.

What can you do:

Always include the network and load balancers as guilty suspects until proven totally innocent. Assure there is a good working relationship between your team and the networking team.


Replication mismanagement (6.1%)

Replication, more specifically OpenDJ/DS replication, can present challenges. DS is also used as the OpenAM/AM Core Token Service (CTS) data store which can add to the level of attention that must be given to replication. Throw in global dispersed data centers and "free-range identities" where, during the life of a session, an identity may visit various and distributed services and properly managing replication is very important.

Like the Halifax Explosion as long as everything operates as expected replication just works. Discrepancies from normal should always be suspect but the downstream effects on any persistent data store and associated replication can be, initially, easy to overlook. Network outages, disk full issues, incorrect or absent sticky sessions, etc can have negative impacts on replication.

Replication must be monitored and managed properly.

Quotes:

Replication status is not real time...people should understand this. - SE

What ForgeRock can do:

The ForgeRock Engineering team is continually enhancing DS to handle environmental issues as well as replication scale in globally dispersed deployments.

What can you do:

Know replication. Assure the operations team fully understand what to monitor and the proper steps to fix problems. Following the proper steps, in the sequence given, is critical. Steps 1, 2, 3 are meant to be performed in that order.



Running out of disk space (5.6%)

Dear children of the 64GB mobile phone age. When I was your age ("oh crap, here it comes" thinks the reader and you are correct) state of the art was a 195MB Data General Zebra disk system. Unit was the size of a real life washing machine and cost over $5,000.00 new. Advancement was when Data General introduced its new Argus 354MB disk for over $30,000.00 and it was about the size of a full size microwave oven. All the cool geeks got one.

Back then, kids, you would think that running out of disk space would be expected. But after the pager went off and after walking uphill (both ways) for miles, through blinding and blowing snow, in cold so bad that penguins were shivering, we would at arrive at the data center, sit over a raised floor with piped cold air directly blowing up your pant legs, and remove unneeded files to free up disk space following the notes we had safely stashed in our pocket protector.

Needless to say when the root cause of a major failure these days is caused by a full disk it is a little hard to comprehend. While the issue may be easy to find making corrections and verifying no data corruption (which can be a lingering issue) is time consuming.

Of all the preventable issues, as the polar bear demonstrates, this one is a real #facepalm.

Quotes:

Note: Due to the unknown sensitivity of the reader the quote has been edited.

oh turdl! ushd! dhfge! - Says anyone involved in this type of event

What ForgeRock can do:

OpenDJ | DS is the most susceptible to this issue - both the data store and logging - as it the part of the platform most responsible for persisting data. There presently are mechanisms within DS to help alleviate disk full issues: https://backstage.forgerock.com/docs/ds/5.5/admin-guide/#set-database-backend-disk-thresholds

While we look at better ways to handle disk full events it is still best practice to never allow a disk full fail in the first place (see Monitoring).

What can you do:

Don't go tight on disk space. Have yet to be in one critical outage where an executive said "well at least we weren't wasting disk space". Monitor disk space constantly; many a system has crumbled on "there was plenty of space last week when we checked".

Abuse of "superuser" account (3.3%)

Since they were invented - superuser, root, admin[istrator], etc - there have been attempts at controlling their awesome power. And for good reason. There are times when overriding built-in checks and controls is absolutely necessary but should NOT become common practice. Fix it properly.

"Hidden" threshold enforcement (aka throttling) (3.0%)

While the Banqiao Dam Collapse speaks to a fail caused by a highly unusual load there are also times when a fail can be caused by efforts to control such loads.

If you run your production environment in the cloud or on any type of virtualized infrastructure understand the provider of such infrastructure is also aware of Banqiao Dam Collapse type events. To prevent the unexpected load of one environment negatively impacting the operation of another environment they place thresholds or throttling in various places such as network throughput or disk IOPs. It is critical to understand these thresholds, what they are, where they are placed, and how and when they are invoked. You may field an environment that you feel can handle X number of transactions per second but in fact can only achieve a lower transaction rate due to throttling. Or the environment can handle the load for a set period of time but due to crossing a threshold all of a sudden transactions start backing up and that cute little spinning thing on the user's app is no longer cute.

Know your platform/infrastructure provider's thresholds | throttling. Otherwise you will discover (eventually) what they are at the most inopportune time i.e. peak load.

Quotes:

Root cause was associated with CLOUD_PROVIDER network bandwidth limitation for the instance type assigned to DS. Initial issue appeared to be AM losing connections with DS and a lower than "normal" transaction rate. - Support ticket

What ForgeRock can do:

Another issue that ForgeRock has limited capability to assist with.

What can you do:

Truly understand all the thresholds and throttling aspects of the environment. This can be a very difficult task as some thresholds kick-in at different points for different instance types or service levels. It is very important to thoroughly test the environment. Assure the test environment is as close to production as possible including component testing. For example if an instance type is supposed to have a threshold of 10,000 IOPs make sure the instance in fact can do 10,000 IOPs and make sure to understand if those are 10,000  IOPs are read IOPs, write IOPs, or a some combination of both.

Noisy neighbor (2.9%)

Sometimes, in virtual environments (cloud, VMware) an instance that is running on the same physical hardware is consuming a large amount of resources. This can cause some significant hidden performance issues. Emphasis on the "hidden".

Noisy neighbor is defined here http://searchcloudcomputing.techtarget.com/definition/noisy-neighbor-cloud-computing-performance

as:

Phrase used to describe a computing infrastructure co-tenant that monopolizes bandwidth, disk I/O, CPU and other resources, and can negatively affect other users' cloud performance. The noisy neighbor effect causes other virtual machines and applications that share the infrastructure to suffer from uneven cloud network performance.

Sometimes noisy neighbors have a pattern. Your environment seems to work just fine except for every Friday at around 04:00pm when for no apparent reason the response time exceeds your SLA. It runs like this for about 4 hours and then returns to expected levels.

What gives? Maybe a late afternoon coffee while you think about it. In the break room you cross paths with one of the DBAs who appears to be just hanging out.

"How's it going?" you ask.

"Fine. Just running the end-of-week recons and backups. Should be out of here around 8 o'clock or so when the jobs complete." replies the DBA.

"So in about 4 hours? You running on bare metal or something else?" You think out loud.

"Yep. Nope. No bare metal anymore. Moved over to the same virtualized environment you folks are running on. Even using the same disk farm I'm sure." says the DBA. "Guess our database jobs really knock the hell out of the environment when they execute!"

"You don't say…." as you leave to seek out the team managing the virtualization platform.

Even at the most basic level achieving consistent performance in a virtualized environment (private cloud, public cloud, bare-metal virtualization) is a challenge. Ran a very simple IO test on a Mac laptop and a virtualized, cloud-based instance. The goal was not which provided the best IO but rather the most consistent IO.



Mac with 8 cores. Notice the straightness of the lines up to "8". This is consistent behaviour as expected on bare-metal. As expected after eight threads things get inconsistent. The threshold - acceptable time for a response - is set to 5ms as the IO test was done against a USB-attached drive. This test was run multiple times all with similar results/graphs.


Now a cloud based instance (16 cores) using the provided disk (no dedicated IO). Threshold for the cloud instance test is set to 8ms as this instance had a hard time of consistently meeting a 5ms threshold which was used with the Mac. The 8ms preset threshold of the testing code is the only straight line. The "passed" operations line crosses the "exceeded" operations line at around 11 threads.


A few minutes later, the exact same instance and the exact same test with the exact same threshold. The graph to the immediate right only goes to 12 threads to make comparison with the Mac easy. The graph to the far right includes the point of intersection where "exceeded" crosses "passed" at around 33 threads.

And within 30 minutes of the first test the final test of the cloud instance. The intersecting point of "passed" vs "exceeded" has reduced to about 28 threads.


The takeaway here is not that you should run your IO-intensive instances on a Macbook Pro. In fact the cloud instance with 16 cores could support, at times, more threads that did not exceed the 8ms threshold. The takeaway is that virtualization and the cloud bring a new dynamic to deployments - a certain level of inconsistency that must be factored in, tested against, and compensated for. For further information here are couple of other pieces of information that shine light on the consistency subject:

  • Datadog - Top 5 ways to improve your AWS EC2 performance: https://www.datadoghq.com/blog/top-5-ways-to-improve-your-aws-ec2-performance/

  • Microsoft - Azure VM Storage Performance and Throttling Demystified: https://blogs.technet.microsoft.com/xiangwu/2017/05/14/azure-vm-storage-performance-and-throttling-demystify/

Note that the Microsoft provided information includes good information about "throttling".

Quotes:

Establish baselines - IO, platform, network latency, ForgeRock out-of-the-box (OOTB). - TA

Response latency is the holy grail and testing is the way to determine what is normal and can be consistently relied on. - PM

What ForgeRock can do:

We continue to assure our products operate properly in a virtualized, dynamic environment. The recent devops guide https://backstage.forgerock.com/docs/platform/5.5/devops-guide/ is an example of the direction ForgeRock is going in the deployment arena.

What can you do:

Issues that don't seem to have a root cause in the ForgeRock platform and appear and disappear for no reason may have their origins in the virtualized infrastructure. If you deploy on a virtualized infrastructure, be it private, managed, or public cloud, include experts on that infrastructure as part of your extended team.

Prepare

We hope that the first time a First Responder needs to use their equipment they are not taking it out of the shrink-wrap and reading the operating instructions. The hope is that the First Responder is well trained and comfortable using whatever they pull from the truck. We hope they have gone through a number of drills and simulated situations so the focus is on saving and not which way they turn the knob to get more water.

Being prepared, being trained, being experienced must be assumed for production environments as well. Here are attributes of successful operators:

  • Create chaos | simulate failures under load. For example:

    • Disable | block API endpoint(s)

    • Stop all traffic requests and/or responses to endpoints

    • Introduce levels of latency - network, IO, and CPU

    • Stop all traffic to a data center or region

    • Randomly terminate a system/service

    • Mess up certificates, DNS, and other core services

    • Do NOT allow testing to be done by developers/operations, they are too kind

    • Simulate DoS both externally and internally

  • Know where log files are located and how to understand them

  • Implement automated build out

  • Consistently verify disaster recovery | high availability works

  • Assure adequate, physically close, disk space for copies/backups i.e. 50M objects in DS: binary copy = ~45GB and LDIF = ~45GB for a potential total of 100GB. Create sample data if needed: https://backstage.forgerock.com/knowledge/kb/article/a67016200

  • Manage and version control configuration artifacts (configuration as code)

    • AM: https://backstage.forgerock.com/knowledge/kb/article/a45857300

    • AM Agents:

    • AM container:
      Use container vendor’s recommended approach

    • AM Token Store - CTS:

    • DS: https://backstage.forgerock.com/knowledge/kb/article/a89103342 & https://backstage.forgerock.com/knowledge/kb/article/a98768700

    • IDM: https://backstage.forgerock.com/docs/openidm/4.5/integrators-guide#chap-advanced

    • IDM repository: Use repository vendor’s recommended approach

    • IG: copy OPENIG_HOME

  • Assure certificates are very well managed

  • and so on…..

    Use repository vendor’s recommended approach

Quote:

Define a list of responsibilities. - i.e,  team A should be looking after resourcing etc., disk space, memory, cpu etc. - SM


Respond

You have attempted to prevent all failures.

You have been trained and are prepared to deal with the unforeseen.

While monitoring the environment you notice something not right. Now what?

You now must respond to the situation in the best way you can. Here are the steps we suggest:

  1. Engage a highly skilled Project Manager and alert at executive level

  2. Engage networking(including load balancers), developers, platform, and if needed:

    1. OpenIDM repository expertise

    2. OpenAM and OpenAM Agent container expertise (i.e. Tomcat, JBOSS, etc)

  3. Thoroughly diagnose the situation
    https://www.scribd.com/doc/24549223/5W-1H-5W-Analysis-Problem-Solving-Technique

  4. Open a ticket and attach most recent configuration data and logs

    1. https://backstage.forgerock.com/knowledge/kb/article/a60648400

    2. https://backstage.forgerock.com/knowledge/kb/article/a51826800

When the Customer Success team (Support team in ForgeRock terminology) was asked what could customers do to better enable ForgeRock to assist the response was quite strong. Here is an example:

For reproducible issues, customers *should be* required to provide step-by-step to reproduce an issue along with screenshots or a video demonstrating the behavior on creating and submitting a case. Other sustaining requirements or acknowledgement (N/A) should be required when creating a case depending on the product in question (i.e. appropriate logs and 3rd Party Product version information such as: java -version + usual out-of-date driver information; "the env + players involved"). A supportability tool/program should be made available to customers, from the UI menu or command line, so as to collect current information from a database or known commands (save large log files) to answer these redundant queries with a small file (zip or text). With the exception of Severity 1 cases (PROD down/biz|mission critical) this will provide Support as much information that is quickly attainable prior to initial research and contact to resolve cases that demand more time and energy from Support. - SE

For all the issues raised above, customer often request for a con-call or screen sharing session when it is not necessary or the issue is not urgent at all. This is time-consuming and counter-productive. Best to gather the required logs and configuration data first. - SE


Conclusion

  1. Focus first on Prevention. This always holds true.

  2. Prepare to fail: put the odds in your favor to succeed.

  3. Monitor all aspects; know what normal looks like.

  4. Respond in a way that helps the helpers help you.



Nomenclature for who provide quotes (ForgeRock staff) : SE = Support | Sustaining Engineer; CSM = Customer Success Manager; TC = Technical Consultant; PM = Product Management; Support Management = SM; TA = Technical Architect
